Interview with Matxin

>You have done great…
We grow, we get stronger. We take the strongest rider to balance the team. It's not like we take four strong riders without knowing where to put them. We take them to put them where we believe we need them. We try to make them grow individually, as Pogacar demonstrated. With all due respect to our rivals, we want to become the number one team in the world.

>Did it surprise you more that Tadej didn't win the Tour or that Ayuso finished on the podium at the Vuelta?
Honestly, I was more surprised that Tadej didn't win the Tour, in the sense that I didn't expect a bad day from him, because he had never had one. But it can happen. Like the first year we won the Tour, when he had a super day and Roglic a completely negative one. It can happen. Obviously when it comes to our advantage, everything looks better, when it happens on the contrary, it hurts (laughs, ed). But cycling is not mathematics. We have a runner who does ordinary things, not extraordinary ones. Tadej doesn't do extraordinary things: he does normal things extraordinarily well.

>Instead Juan?
Compared to Ayuso… You know the friendship that exists and the steps that made him take it. He has always listened to advice, he has always believed in it. I knew he could be far ahead, but in professionalism many times you don't know where you can go: not because of your level, but because you find it hard to understand that of your rivals. That is why they must always be respected. Then of course there are the many variables. It happened that he crashed and maybe he could not have made the podium. This is why we started with Almeida as leader and with Ayuso behind, covering him and not putting pressure on him. We wanted to see what he would do, day by day, especially after the tenth / twelfth stage. The limit of his stages was the Giro U23, which lasts 10 days. You can't ask a 19-year-old boy for anything other than to make the best of himself.

(cont.)

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>127918959
>You talked about Almeida: how do you evaluate his career?
I've known Joao since he was a junior and I've lived through his progression. I remember when he went to Trevigiani because he needed a team like that, in which he made a qualitative step by winning two races. Then we realized he needed to go with Axel Merckx to the Hagens Berman Axeon. So I helped him transition to Quick Step and then here at UAE. The problem is that even if a rider is growing perfectly, when he takes the pink jersey for 15 days, he seems condemned to win it the following year. Instead Joao is taking the right steps, very right. I'm really happy, but in recent years he has also had bad luck.

>When?
Without Covid at the 2022 Giro d'Italia, I am convinced that he was at least third. I don't know if more, but a third did it (the Portuguese stopped after the 14th stage when he was in fourth position, ed). Then he prepared for the Vuelta, but came back late to recover well. He raced in Burgos, went to high altitudes and suffered a lot in the first week of the race. And he improved and finished fifth. He had two precise moments - the Covid in the Giro and the Vuelta in which he started with his left foot - but otherwise I'm happy with how he moved. He went to Catalonia and showed that he could beat the best in the world, he went to the most important races and was at a very high level. I am convinced that next year Almeida will take another step forward.

>Do you think those 15 days in the pink jersey have become a burden?
No, he didn't suffer them. He was and will still be our leader in the Giro d'Italia, without a doubt. But he lived what will probably happen to Juanpe Lopez in 2023, with all my respect. After his 10 days in the pink jersey and the tenth place finish, if he finishes twelfth next year, it will look like he didn't do anything. But it's not a mathematical question.

(cont.)

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>127918977
>Meaning what?
Almeida is taking his steps progressively. Nobody expected him to be a winner this year or last year when he finished sixth, or two years ago when he took the pink jersey for 15 days. But it's always growing and for this I'm really happy. He is professional and respectful. At the UAE Tour he pulled for Tadej like a fan and himself finished fifth. If he hadn't shot so hard the day Tadej won, he would have been second or third at most. This means that he has a big heart. It is very easy to work with smart and smart guys like Tadej and Joao. There is a beautiful atmosphere, you can see it here too. There is respect between them, they are intelligent, they know that together they can be stronger than alone. For this I am satisfied.

>In the meantime, the team is growing around…
I think everything has to be balanced, for the same reason we don't pick riders at random. If we have to ask everyone for 120 percent, we have to give them 120 percent. Indeed, many times it is important to give it first, and then ask for it. For this reason, even as a team we always try to give our best. We can do this by giving the best staff, the best material, the best hotels, the best trainers, recovery. We have to choose only the one that is the top. We don't just have to find the best rider in the world, we have to be the best team in the world to find the best in the world.

>Do you also study your opponents?
Yes, a lot. Two years ago it was Quick Step who always won the team classification, now who would you bet on? As for young people. Everyone asks me if the Tour will again be a fight between Tadej and Vingegaard, but are you convinced that there won't be someone else? They were expecting Remco Evenepoel and Ayuso and now we have to believe that no one will turn up? It will come, I guarantee it. For this we must look not only to the side, but as externally as possible. Because nobody goes back, they are coming from all sides. (cut the last sentence)

One of the SI people posted on the official forum that the youth formula factors in your youth coaches' JPP and WYY to come up with the "freak" newgens' PA (which is basically all you give a fuck about). I think the average ones' PA is more tied to facilities and club rep. Plus obviously the coaches' personalities are important. I hire youth coaches considering ONLY those factors (JPP, WWY, and personality) and I got about 5 golden generations in a row on my way up through the leagues in Italy that way. Also produced a wonderkid who's worth like 70 million right now and in my sería A first team at 19. You can still have bad classes but generally they'll be better than average. I had my first dud last season and my youth team still goes undefeated in its league, guys get called up for Italy youth teams, etc. Basically the coaching attributes don't matter because if the players have good personalities they'll develop no matter what. The personalities are still mostly random though. Also, I suspect that your first team coaches factor in too even though they said youth coaches. Some of the kids have first team coaches as favored personnel if you look at their profiles and that's who I assume influences their attributes. You're still going to be limited somewhat by club rep and what country you're in but you can get some of the better prospects in your country by doing it that way at least

If he stuck to his guns on offense he would have fallen off after 2015 or so. Saban reloads his staff every offseason with good new hires, which is another hurdle that has ended many dynasties. No other dynasty managed to avoid the usual pitfalls of the game passing them by and making bad assistant hires and NCAA sanctions and the head coach just losing his edge for this long and it will probably never happen again.

That said, nothing lasts forever. There are no sure things in coaching hires. There is a 0% chance Saban's replacement performs at the same level he did, but he'll have to be close to keep Bama in the title contender tier. There will be some dropoff no matter how much momentum and talent Saban leaves behind because the only way to go is down when replacing the GOAT. Their fanbase doesn't have as much money as some of the bigger money NIL teams but Saban can still get pretty much anyone he wants thanks to his long record of success. After he retires Bama won't be able to sell as many recruits on "Take less in NIL now for more in the NFL later" because that's a Saban pitch. Georgia, LSU and Tennessee are all on the rise. Auburn can always meme their way to 11 wins, A&M might get their shit together some day and when Texas and Oklahoma join the SEC recruiting will get more difficult because those two will start landing guys who previously weren't interested in playing in the Big 12. If Bama was in a trash conference like the ACC it would be a lot easier for their next head coach to keep them on top.

>>127909601
Low volume high repetitions.
Because you are fasting you will be low energy and your performance and recovery will suffer.
If you do 8-16 fasts then you can exercises almost normally, just keep the volume low, save 2-3 sets in the tank (assuming you usually work with relatively high volume) and save 2-3 reps too (same thing but for intensity, if your volume and intensity isn't that high to begin with just drop 1 set) this will ensure that you can handle it while low on energy, will help to maintain muscle (as long as your protein intake is good) and burn more calories.
Personally I don't like fasting, i think is good for fat guys but if you are already low bodyfat i think is more effective that during cutting phases you eat at maintenance and work enough so you are still at a caloric deficit.
The routines are more demanding like this but the diet is more sustainable than being in a deficit and fasting isn't suitable for long term weight loss.
Is ok to fast for some periods but try different methods to lose weight if that's your goal (if it's medical because of your condition then listen to your doc, you better not be fasting because of fit memes)
